  <p>
    In this post, I would like to look into Anova hypothesis testing. The dataset I am going to use is published in <a href="https://smartcities.data.gov.in" class="uri">https://smartcities.data.gov.in</a> which is a Government of India project under the National Data Sharing and Accessibility Policy.
  </p>
  
  <p>
    I want to analyse if the unemployment across Bangalore is similar or are there pockets with high unemployment. The <a href="https://smartcities.data.gov.in/catalog/city-profile-bengaluru?filters%5Bfield_catalog_reference%5D=2916949&format=json&offset=0&limit=9&sort%5Bcreated%5D=desc">Unemployment_Rate_Bengaluru.csv</a> dataset has total employed and unemployed people in Bangalore at a Ward level. For simplicity sake, I want to concentrate on three zones, Bangalore-east, Mahadevpura and Rajeshwari Nagar.
  </p>
  
  <p>
    As I want to test that there is significant difference between unemployment rate in different zones in Bangalore, the null and alternate hypothesis will be as follows:<br /> H<sub></sub>: μ<sub>Bangalore-east</sub> = μ<sub>Mahadevpura</sub> = μ<sub>Rajeshwari-Nagar</sub><br /> H<sub>1</sub>: Not all μ are equal
  </p>
  
  <p>
    Sample unemployment data set:
  </p>
  
  <pre><code>## # A tibble: 5 x 8

    Visualizing the difference of unemployment in each zone.
  </p>

  <p>
    From the above table I observe that the unemployment rate is between 54% and 57% in all the three zones.
  </p>
  
  <p>
    One of the conditions to perform anova is that the population response variable follows a normal distribution in each group. The distribution of unemployment rate in diffeent zones are:
  </p>
  
  <pre class="r"><code>ggplot() + 
  geom_density(data=unemployment, aes(x=rate, group=zoneName, color=zoneName), adjust=2) +
  labs(x = 'Unemployment Rate', y='Density',  title = 'Testing normality among response variables') +
  theme_minimal()+theme(legend.position="bottom")</code></pre>
  
  <p>
    <img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
  </p>
  
  <p>
    From the above graph, it looks like the three groups are normally distributed. To test for normality, we could use Shapiro-Wilk test.<br /> The test for each group would have the following hypothesis:<br /> H<sub></sub>: The unemployment rate in the group is normally distributed<br /> H<sub>1</sub>: The unemployment rate in the group is not normally distributed
  </p>
  
  <pre class="r"><code>for(i in 1:nrow(data.summary)){
  test.dist &lt;- (unemployment %&gt;% dplyr::filter(zoneName == data.summary$group[i]))$rate
  cat('Testing for group ', data.summary$group[i], '\n')
  print(shapiro.test(test.dist))
  norm.plot &lt;- ggplot() + 
    geom_qq(aes(sample = test.dist)) +
    stat_qq_line(aes(sample = test.dist)) +
    ggtitle(paste0("Normal distribution Q-Q plot for group ",data.summary$group[i])) +
    theme_minimal()
  plot(norm.plot)
}</code></pre>
  
  <pre><code>## Testing for group  East 
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  test.dist
## W = 0.97147, p-value = 0.06734</code></pre>
  
  <p>
    <img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
  </p>
  
  <pre><code>## Testing for group  Mahadevapura 
##

  <p>
    <img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
  </p>
  
  <pre><code>## Testing for group  Rajarajeswari Nagar

  <p>
    As p > α, where α = 0.01, retaining the Null hypothesis in all the three groups. Therefore we can assume that unemployment rate is normally distributed among all groups.
  </p>
  
  <p>
    Another condition for anova is that the population variances are assumed to be same. This is an assumption I am willing to take at this point.
  </p>
  
  <p>
    Taking these assumptions, the ideal distributions of the sample are as follows. These distributions can be compared to a <a href="https://harshaash.shinyapps.io/AnovaSimulation/">simulation</a> that I created where change in F value (and significance of anova) can be visualised by increasing the between variance (increasing the distance between group means)
  </p>
  
  <pre class="r"><code>plot.normal.groups &lt;- function(data.summary, mean, sd, label, title){
  common.group.sd &lt;- mean(data.summary$sd)
  range &lt;- seq(mean-3*sd, mean+3*sd, by = sd*0.001)
  norm.dist &lt;- data.frame(range = range, dist = dnorm(x = range, mean = mean, sd = sd))
  # Plotting sampling distribution and x_bar value with cutoff
  norm.aov.plot &lt;- ggplot(data = norm.dist, aes(x = range,y = dist))
  for (i in 1:nrow(data.summary)) {
    norm.aov.plot &lt;- norm.aov.plot + 
      stat_function(fun = dnorm, color=colors()[sample(50:100, 1)],  size = 1, 
                    args = list(mean = data.summary$mean[i], sd = common.group.sd))
  }
  norm.aov.plot + labs(x = label, y='Density',  title = title) +
      theme_minimal()+theme(legend.position="bottom")
}
set.seed(9)
mean &lt;- mean(unemployment$rate)
sd &lt;- sd(unemployment$rate)
plot.normal.groups(data.summary, mean, sd, 'Travel time (sec)', 'Assuming normality among response variables')</code></pre>
  
  <p>
    <img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
  </p>
  
  <p>
    Performing Anova with<br /> H<sub></sub>: μ<sub>Bangalore-east</sub> = μ<sub>Mahadevpura</sub> = μ<sub>Rajeshwari-Nagar</sub><br /> H<sub>1</sub>: Not all μ are equal
  </p>
  
  <pre class="r"><code># Functions used in anova-test

f.plot &lt;- function(pop.mean=0, alpha = 0.05, f, df1, df2,
                              label = 'F distribution',title = 'Anova test'){
  # Creating a sample F distribution
  range &lt;- seq(qf(0.0001, df1, df2), qf(0.9999, df1, df2), by = (qf(0.9999, df1, df2)-qf(0.0001, df1, df2))*0.001)
  f.dist &lt;- data.frame(range = range, dist = df(x = range, ncp = pop.mean, df1 = df1, df2 = df2)) %&gt;% 
    dplyr::mutate(H0 = if_else(range &lt;= qf(p = 1-alpha, ncp = pop.mean, df1 = df1,df2 = df2),'Retain', 'Reject'))
  # Plotting sampling distribution and F value with cutoff
  plot.test &lt;- ggplot(data = f.dist, aes(x = range,y = dist)) +
    geom_area(aes(fill = H0)) +
    scale_color_manual(drop = TRUE, values = c('Retain' = "#00BFC4", 'Reject' = "#F8766D"), aesthetics = 'fill') +
    geom_vline(xintercept = f, size = 2) +
    geom_text(aes(x = f, label = paste0('F = ', round(f,3)), y = mean(dist)), colour="blue", vjust = 1.2) +
    labs(x = label, y='Density',  title = title) +
    theme_minimal()+theme(legend.position="bottom")
  plot(plot.test)
}</code></pre>
  
  <pre class="r"><code>anva &lt;- aov(rate ~ zoneName, unemployment)
anova.summary &lt;- summary(anva)
print(anova.summary)</code></pre>
  
  <pre><code>##              Df  Sum Sq  Mean Sq F value Pr(&gt;F)  
## zoneName      2 0.01065 0.005323   3.315 0.0397 *
## Residuals   120 0.19269 0.001606                 
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1</code></pre>
  
  <pre class="r"><code>f.plot(f = anova.summary[[1]]$F[1], df1 = anova.summary[[1]]$Df[1], df2 = anova.summary[[1]]$Df[2])</code></pre>
  
  <p>
    <img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
  </p>
  
  <p>
    Here p < α, where α = 0.05 Hence rejecting the Null Hypothesis. From this test we can observe that not all groups have same mean. But to find out which groups are similar and which are different, I am conducting a TukeyHSD test.
  </p>
  
  <pre class="r"><code>tukey.test &lt;- TukeyHSD(anva)
print(tukey.test)</code></pre>
  
  <pre><code>##   Tukey multiple comparisons of means
##     95% family-wise confidence level
## 
## Fit: aov(formula = rate ~ zoneName, data = unemployment)
## 
## $zoneName
##                                          diff         lwr          upr

## Rajarajeswari Nagar-East         -0.026768634 -0.05154855 -0.001988723
## Rajarajeswari Nagar-Mahadevapura -0.019696735 -0.04934803  0.009954561
##                                      p adj
## Mahadevapura-East                0.7285538
## Rajarajeswari Nagar-East         0.0309193
## Rajarajeswari Nagar-Mahadevapura 0.2597730</code></pre>
  
  <pre class="r"><code># Plot pairwise TukeyHSD comparisons and color by significance level
tukey.df &lt;- as.data.frame(tukey.test$zoneName)
tukey.df$pair = rownames(tukey.df)
ggplot(tukey.df, aes(colour=cut(`p adj`, c(0, 0.01, 0.05, 1), 
                           label=c("p&lt;0.01","p&lt;0.05","Non-Sig")))) +
  geom_hline(yintercept=0, lty="11", colour="grey30") +
  geom_errorbar(aes(pair, ymin=lwr, ymax=upr), width=0.2) +
  geom_point(aes(pair, diff)) +
  labs(x = 'Groups', y='Density',  colour="", title = 'Tukey HSD Test') +
    theme_minimal()+theme(legend.position="bottom")</code></pre>
  
  <p>
    <img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
  </p>
  
  <p>
    From this test we can see that there is significant difference (with α = 0.05 confidence) between Rajeshwari Nagar and Bangalore East.
  </p>
